// `finally { ... }` arms a finalizer of the current agent instance (Go-`defer`-like): armed blocks run
// in reverse arming order right before the instance acknowledges its terminal — a normal completion or
// a cancellation — and never on a panic. Arming the same statement twice (e.g. in a loop body) arms it
// twice; that stack discipline is the point, not a defect.
//
// A finalizer runs while the parent may already be awaiting this instance's cancellation, so its net
// effect must stay within `io`: it may not escalate a request through that parent (io routes to sibling
// reactors instead). A request RAISED and HANDLED locally inside the finalizer body is discharged, so it
// is fine; an UNHANDLED request that would escape is rejected at compile time (K3021).

@"A cleanup capability, provided and discharged INSIDE the finalizer that uses it."
request cleanup() -> null

@"Arm two finalizers before returning. They run in reverse arming order — the `cleanup` one first, then
the note — right before this instance acknowledges completion (and on cancellation, but never on a
panic). The first finalizer is pure; the second raises `cleanup`, but a handler INSIDE it discharges the
request, so nothing escalates to a parent that may already be awaiting this instance's cancellation, and
its net effect stays within `io`. (Richer finalizers that write a real log line arrive with the runtime's
io prims; until then a finalizer keeps to `io` or a locally-handled request like this.)"
agent run() -> string {
  finally { let _note = "bookkeeping done" }
  finally {
    use handler {
      request cleanup() -> null { next null }
    }
    let _released = cleanup()
  }
  "work complete"
}
